  "why": "The CrossASR++ framework generates test inputs (audio) from a predefined text corpus using Text-to-Speech (TTS) engines. This design inherently enforces both semantic consistency and naturalness. Semantic consistency is strictly maintained because the original text from the corpus serves as the unwavering ground truth for the generated audio; the text itself is not mutated. Naturalness is enforced by using TTS engines, which are designed to produce realistic human speech. The framework also includes a mechanism to filter out implausible inputs: if no ASR system can correctly transcribe an audio file, it is flagged as an 'indeterminable test case' and effectively discarded, under the assumption that the TTS generated invalid audio. Because each test case is generated independently from a text source rather than through iterative mutation of a previous audio input, the problem of cumulative distortion across fuzzing iterations is completely avoided. This aligns with the 'High' rating's criteria of fixing semantically critical content and ensuring realism.",
